structured.description: A `PageInfo` class that contains information about a page of data. It has four fields: `currentPage`, `pageLimit`, `totalPages`, and `totalElements`. These fields are initialized using a constructor that takes a `Pageable` object and a `Page` object as parameters. A static `of` method creates a new `PageInfo` instance based on the pageable and page arguments passed to it.

items.description: Is a data structure that encapsulates information about a page of results in a larger dataset. It contains the current page being viewed, the maximum number of pages allowed, and the total number of pages and elements in the dataset. The class also provides a method for creating a new instance of PageInfo from a Pageable object and its associated page.
items.name: PageInfo

items.description: Generates a `PageInfo` object that contains information about the number of pages and elements in a paginated collection, given a `Pageable` object and an instance of the page type.

params.name: pageable
params.description: pagination information for the data being processed, providing the page number, page size, total pages, and total elements.

params.name: page
params.description: current page being processed, providing information on its position and size within the overall dataset.

returns.description: a `PageInfo` object containing page number, page size, total pages, and total elements.

items.name: of

structured.description: An API for managing amenities in a community. It provides endpoints for listing all amenities, listing amenities for a specific community, adding a new amenity, deleting an existing amenity, and updating an existing amenity. The API uses Spring Boot packages such as Spring Web Flux, Spring Data JPA, and Lombok to handle HTTP requests, validate request bodies, map objects to DTOs, and log debug messages.

items.description: Provides RESTful APIs for managing amenities in a community. The controller handles requests to get all amenities, list all amenities for a specific community, add new amenities, delete existing amenities, and update existing amenities. The controller utilizes dependencies with the AmenityService and AmenityApiMapper classes to perform these operations.
items.name: AmenityController

items.description: Retrieves amenity details for a given ID using a JPA service and maps the response to an `AmenityDetailsResponse`. It returns an `OK` response if the amenity is found, or a `NOT_FOUND` response otherwise.

params.name: amenityId
params.description: identifier of the amenity for which details are requested.

returns.description: an `ResponseEntity` object representing a successful response with an `OK` status and the requested amenity details.

items.name: getAmenityDetails

items.description: Retrieves a list of amenities from the database using `amenitySDJpaService`, maps them to `GetAmenityDetailsResponse` set using `amenityApiMapper`, and returns an `ResponseEntity` with the mapped response.

params.name: communityId
params.description: ID of the community whose amenities will be listed.

returns.description: a set of `GetAmenityDetailsResponse` objects containing the details of all amenities for a given community.

items.name: listAllAmenities

items.description: Adds amenities to a community using the `amenitySDJpaService`. It creates a list of amenities, maps it to a response entity, and returns it as a successful response if the amenities are added successfully.

params.name: communityId
params.description: id of the community to which the amenities will be added.

params.name: request
params.description: AddAmenityRequest object containing the amenities to be added to the community.

returns.description: a `ResponseEntity` object representing a successful addition of amenities to a community, with a status code of `ok`.

items.name: addAmenityToCommunity

items.description: Deletes an amenity from the database based on the specified `amenityId`. If successful, it returns a `ResponseEntity` with a status code of `NO_CONTENT`. If unsuccessful, it returns a `ResponseEntity` with a status code of `NOT_FOUND`.

params.name: amenityId
params.description: ID of an amenity to be deleted.

returns.description: a `ResponseEntity` object with a status code of either `NO_CONTENT` or `NOT_FOUND`, depending on whether the amenity was successfully deleted.

items.name: deleteAmenity

items.description: Updates an amenity's details using a `UpdateAmenityRequest` object, and returns a response entity indicating whether the update was successful or not.

params.name: amenityId
params.description: ID of the amenity being updated.

params.name: request
params.description:
UpdateAmenityRequest object containing the details of the amenity to be updated, which is then converted into an AmenityDto object and passed to the updateAmenity method of the amenitySDJpaService for updates.

* `@Valid`: Indicates that the request body must contain a valid JSON object representing an update amenity request.
* `@RequestBody`: Represents the request body as a JSON object, which is used to map the request data to the `AmenityDto` class.

returns.description:
a `ResponseEntity` object with a status code indicating whether the amenity was successfully updated or not.

* The response entity is of type `ResponseEntity`, which indicates that the operation was successful.
* The status code of the response entity is `HttpStatus.NO_CONTENT`, indicating that the amenity was updated successfully.
* The `build()` method is used to create a new response entity with the specified status code and headers.

usage.description:
The method updateAmenity takes in two arguments:
* amenityId of type string, which represents the unique identifier for an amenity.
* request of type UpdateAmenityRequest, which contains information about the amenity that needs to be updated.

items.name: updateAmenity

structured.description: An interface for an amenity service that allows for the creation, retrieval, deletion, and updating of amenities within a community. The interface includes several methods: createAmenities, getAmenityDetails, deleteAmenity, listAllAmenities, and updateAmenity. These methods allow for the management of amenities in a structured and organized manner.

structured.description: A custom UserDetailsService class named AppUserDetailsService which implements Spring's UserDetailsService interface. It uses Spring Data JPA's UserRepository and a custom UserMapper to fetch user data from the database and convert it into a UserDetails object. The code also includes a method getUserDetailsByUsername to retrieve a UserDto based on a given username.

items.description: Is a custom implementation of UserDetailsService, responsible for retrieving user details from a database and mapping them to a UserDetails object. It utilizes UserRepository and UserMapper to fetch and transform data. The class provides two methods: loadUserByUsername and getUserDetailsByUsername.
items.name: AppUserDetailsService

items.description: Retrieves a user with a specified email address from a database using a repository, and if found, returns a UserDetails object representing that user, otherwise throws an exception. The returned object includes the user's email, encrypted password, and boolean flags indicating account enabled and locked status.

params.name: username
params.description: email address of the user to be retrieved from the database and validated.

returns.description:
a `UserDetails` object representing the authenticated user.

The returned object is an instance of the `UserDetails` class with the following attributes - email address, encrypted password, and a collection of authorities (empty in this case).

items.name: loadUserByUsername

items.description: Retrieves a `User` entity from the database by its email address, which is provided as a username parameter. If the user is not found, it throws a `UsernameNotFoundException`. Otherwise, it converts the retrieved user to a `UserDto` object and returns it.

params.name: username
params.description: username to be used for searching and retrieving user details from the database using the `userRepository`.

items.name: getUserDetailsByUsername

structured.description: An interface for community management services using Spring Data. The interface provides methods for creating, listing, retrieving, and managing communities, their houses, admins, and other related data. It utilizes Pageable for pagination and Optional for handling null or empty results. The interface covers various operations such as adding/removing admins and houses from a community, deleting a community, and more.

items.description: Provides various operations for managing communities, community houses, and user roles within a community in a social network application.
items.name: CommunityService

structured.description: An interface AmenityRepository that extends JpaRepository, a Spring Data JPA repository interface. It provides two methods for retrieving Amenities by their ID: one method fetches additional data (community) related to the amenity and returns it as Optional, while the other method only returns the amenity itself without additional data.

items.description: Extends JpaRepository and provides two methods for retrieving an Amenity by its ID, with optional fetching of related data.
items.name: AmenityRepository

structured.description: A Spring Data JPA repository named CommunityRepository that interacts with a database table representing communities. It provides multiple query methods for retrieving and querying community data by community ID, including fetching related entities such as houses, admins, and amenities using EntityGraph annotations. Additionally, it includes a method to check if a community exists in the database.

structured.description: An Entity class named Amenity which is part of a larger system utilizing JPA (Java Persistence API) and Hibernate. The entity represents a type of amenity that can be associated with communities or community houses. It has properties like ID, name, description, price, and references to the related entities.

items.description: Represents an entity in a database with attributes such as ID, name, description and price, along with relationships to Community, CommunityHouse and BookingItem entities.

fields.name: amenityId
fields.description: is a non-nullable unique identifier for an Amenity entity.

fields.name: name
fields.description: is a mandatory string field with no unique constraints.

fields.name: description
fields.description: in Amenity class is a non-null, non-unique string representing a brief text about an amenity.

fields.name: price
fields.description: represents the monetary value of an amenity.

fields.name: community
fields.description: represents a many-to-one relationship with the Community entity.

fields.name: communityHouse
fields.description: in Amenity represents a one-to-many relationship with CommunityHouse entities.

fields.name: bookingItems
fields.description: represents a collection of AmenityBookingItem objects that are associated with this Amenity instance.

items.name: Amenity

structured.description: An application that is based on Spring Boot framework. It scans for configuration properties and enables auto-configuration of beans. The application also configures a BCrypt password encoder for securing passwords.

items.description: Initializes and configures a Spring Boot application with security features. It defines a main method to start the application and registers a password encoder bean using BCryptPasswordEncoder. The class also enables configuration properties scanning.
items.name: MyHomeServiceApplication

items.description: Launches an application using the Spring Boot framework. It runs a class named `MyHomeServiceApplication`, passing command-line arguments to it. This initializes and starts the application.

params.name: args
params.description: command-line arguments passed to the application when it is run.

items.name: main

items.description: Defines a bean to configure password encoding using the BCrypt algorithm. It returns an instance of `BCryptPasswordEncoder`, which can be used to hash and verify passwords securely. This implementation provides a strong password hashing mechanism for authentication purposes.

usage.description: It creates an instance of MyHomeServiceApplication, retrieves the PasswordEncoder, and uses it to encrypt a given password.

items.name: getPasswordEncoder

structured.description: A test class AppJwtParamTest that tests the creation of an instance of the AppJwt class using a builder pattern. The AppJwt class is built with a user ID and expiration time, which is set to the current local date and time.

items.description: Is a test class containing a single test method to validate the creation of an AppJwt object using its builder pattern. The test creates an instance of AppJwt with specific parameters and prints it to the console. This test ensures that the AppJwt object can be successfully created with valid user information and expiration date.
items.name: AppJwtParamTest

items.description: Creates an instance of the `AppJwt` class using a builder pattern, specifying a user ID and expiration date set to the current time. The resulting object is then printed to the console.
items.name: testParamCreationBuilder

structured.description: A configuration class that sets up email templates and message sources for an application using Spring and Thymeleaf. It uses ResourceBundleMessageSource and SpringTemplateEngine to configure the templates and messages. The code also resolves the template paths and suffixes based on provided properties and settings.

items.description: Is responsible for configuring email templates using Thymeleaf and ResourceBundleMessageSource. It provides beans for message source and template engine, which can be used to render email templates based on locale and encoding settings.
items.name: EmailTemplateConfig

items.description: Initializes a `ResourceBundleMessageSource` bean, setting its properties from the `localizationProperties`. It specifies the resource bundle file name, default locale, encoding, and cache seconds for message retrieval. The function returns the configured `ResourceBundleMessageSource` instance.
items.name: emailMessageSource

items.description: Configures a Spring Template Engine for Thymeleaf, setting up a resolver for templates and an engine message source from ResourceBundleMessageSource.

params.name: emailMessageSource
params.description: ResourceBundleMessageSource used to resolve messages and text for Thymeleaf templates by the SpringTemplateEngine.

items.name: thymeleafTemplateEngine

items.description: Creates and configures a Thymeleaf template resolver instance. It sets various properties such as prefix, suffix, template mode, character encoding, and cacheability based on input values from the `templateProperties`. The configured resolver is then returned for use.

returns.description:
a configured Thymeleaf template resolver object.

Set prefix specifies the directory where templates are located. 
Suffix is set to a specific format for the template files. 
Template mode determines how templates will be processed. 
Character encoding specifies the character set used in the template files. 
Cacheable property controls whether or not the resolved templates can be cached.

items.name: thymeleafTemplateResolver

structured.description: A class called HouseDetailResponse that represents a response object for house details. It is annotated with Lombok annotations @NoArgsConstructor, @AllArgsConstructor, and @Data which generate boilerplate getters and setters. The class has one private field "house" of type CommunityHouseDto.

items.description: Represents a response model for creating a user request, encapsulating essential details such as user ID, name, and email.

fields.name: userId
fields.description: represents an identifier for a user in the CreateUserResponse model.

fields.name: name
fields.description: represents a string value for the user's name in the CreateUserResponse model.

items.name: CreateUserResponse

structured.description: A Spring-based configuration class to enable CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing) in a web application. It uses the WebMvcConfigurer interface to customize the behavior of the Spring MVC framework. The code allows CORS for all URLs ("/**") and specifies the allowed origins, methods, headers, and exposed headers.

items.description: Configures cross-origin resource sharing (CORS) for a web application. It defines a bean that enables CORS support and specifies allowed origins, methods, headers, and exposed headers. The class also allows credentials and applies the configuration to all endpoints.
items.name: CorsConfig

items.description: Enables CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing) for a web application, allowing requests from any origin, with all HTTP methods, and exposing specific headers (`token` and `userId`) to handle cross-origin authentication.

returns.description:
a configuration for CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing) in Spring MVC.

Define a mapping with any path pattern by using the addMapping method. The allowedOrigins property allows access from a specific set of origins. The allowedMethods and allowedHeaders methods allow all HTTP methods and headers respectively. ExposedHeaders is used to specify which headers can be accessed. AllowCredentials is set to true for enabling credentials in the request.

usage.description: This configuration enables cross-origin resource sharing for all URLs in the application.

items.name: corsConfigurer

items.description: Defines CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing) settings for a web application. It enables cross-origin requests by mapping all URLs ("/**") and allowing specific origins, methods, headers, and exposed headers. Additionally, it allows credentials to be sent with the request.

params.name: registry
params.description: instance responsible for managing CORS mappings, which are used to define the configuration for Cross-Origin Resource Sharing.

usage.code:
CorsRegistry registry = new CorsRegistry();
registry.addMapping("/**")
    .allowedOrigins(new String[] {"http://example.com"})
    .allowedMethods("*")
    .allowedHeaders("*")
    .exposedHeaders("token", "userId")
    .allowCredentials(true);
usage.description: Note: The input 'CorsRegistry' is passed as a parameter to method 'addCorsMappings'.

items.name: addCorsMappings
